metadata.name: Mur #25
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: Quantum Vacuum #253
metadata.description:
Empty space is not empty. It's filled with energy, transient fluctuations in quantum fields, bubbling with virtual particles popping in and out of existence. 

Part of an ongoing series of work combining my fascination with the fringes of fundamental physics, the emergence of complex behaviour through the interaction of very simple rules, and my obsession with hacking our perceptual systems. 

/Disclaimer: This is not a simulation, but an artistic conceptual interpretation and dramatization. :)

4’33’” - a 3-movement composition by experimental composer John Cage. 

4’33” - THE MUSIC.  Cage wrote the score instructing performers not to play their instruments during the entire duration of the piece. Though it is often perceived as silence, it is in that context: the sounds of the environment, being that, it becomes music.  

4’33” - fx(hash) gentk, you get a flatpack stained glass tea hut. Your tea hut, prefabbed with fixed geometry and fixed color palette straight out of the box. 

The code interprets your hash as pertaining to where and how you build this hut. Though it might look like noise or glitch, it is in the context: the light in us colors the shadows, reflections, celebrations of life, and acts in life.  

If you listen c a . r .    e .    f .      u .     l .        l.        y you can hear the reverberation, sounds of splendid joy in it. 

p5.js may take about 4.33 seconds to draw. Press 1 to save png.

metadata.name: Reconnaissance #209
metadata.description:
An immense quiet accompanies a sense of looming futility while peering down across vast new worlds. What use is there in discovering and documenting these unknown places? Who would care to seek out lifeless lands lost in the cosmos?

Any civilization capable of such reconnaissance might seem above the little hope that barren lands may bring. Unless, of course, there is a hope of answering the most desperate of needs: Finding a New Home.

Were these images captured by humans on Earth, or on Mars, or somewhere even further away in distance and probability? Maybe they’re recon from another planet’s civilization — one that shares our struggle to find true harmony with the world they have.

Inspired by the remarkable satellite imagery in the compendium “This is Mars,” Reconnaissance suggests what may lie outside our habitable lands — and that we risk missing what's already here while being compelled to look further and further for what’s next.


Choose a resolution (1-6) by adding "&scale=4" to the URL in live view.
Created with p5.js

TENDER x Nat Sarkissian
May 2022

metadata.name: Refractions #109
metadata.description:
Refractions is a study of frequencies, harmonies and abstract representations of natural phenomena. 

It is an experiment of blending three colors to create integrated textural compositions.


Probabilities;

- 14 compositions with variations.

- 2 background color.

- 19 different base color palette (2 monochrome).

- 2 distinct textures with variations.

-  2 different alpha types; tangential & sinusoidal.

- Different edges.

- Several starting positions and styles (wavy or straight).


Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, April 2022
@distcollective

metadata.name: Antiflow #67
metadata.description:
"Opposites are not contradictory but complementary." - Niels Bohr

The concept of yin and yang is an ancient philosophy about how opposing forces are not only complementary but actually give rise to each other. This idea reverberates through nature, art, and life itself. Now it is at the heart of modern physics. Perhaps this is a fundamental law of nature baked into the very fabric of existence.

Antiflow is an exploration of how balanced complexity can arise from chaos by harnessing the dynamic interplay of opposing forces. To that end we were inspired to create this wildly unique set by mixing modern physics concepts with abstract expressionism and retro 3D primitives.

The aspect ratio is 3:2 to facilitate poster size prints and device wallpapers. Results are presented without borders, noise, or other effects to allow for maximum detail. Feel free to rotate in whatever direction you choose for the best display.

Press "S" to save at a higher definition.

metadata.name: TV Test-Blocks #27
metadata.description: These TV test blocks generated from my base experimental code named "Mind Blocks" on Processing4. The TV test patterns is widely recognized as one of the iconic populer culture symbols of the 1980s and 1990s. Numerous novelty and collectible items has been patterned after the famous test card, including wall clocks, badseets, wristwatches, and clothing (wiki says). So why shouldn't they find a place for themselves as generative token?

metadata.name: Pandora #76
metadata.description:
Pandora received many gifts from the Gods: beauty, flattery, kindness, skill, grace, intelligence, but also the art of deception and seduction. They gave her the name Pandora (Πανδώρα), “endowed with all the gifts” in Greek.

The Pandora generative series has the same qualities as the mythological figure. Able to adopt many different shapes, a wide variety of colors and styles, all created from simple rules.

Only one thing though, do not open the box.

[S] key to save a PNG image
Press once for a resolution of 2000x2000, a second time for a resolution of 4000x4000, then 6000x6000 and finally 8000x8000

Made with p5.js

Artist: Estienne
April 2022
